The Education Ministry has raised concerns over the low number of candidates registered for this year&rsquo;s KCPE and KCSE exams.Basic Education PS Belio Kipsang on Saturday said the ministry aimed to register about one million candidates for the KCPE exam, and 600,000 for KCSE.But only 350,000 candidates had been registered for the KCPE exam and less than 100,000 for KCSE by last Wednesday.Kipsang urged head teachers to register candidates before the February 28 deadline.He addressed officials of the Kenya Secondary School Heads&rsquo; Association. Kipsang said the government has set aside Sh3.2 billion to pay examination fees for all KCPE and KCSE candidates, including candidates from private schools.He said the government plans to build more secondary schools to accomodate more pupils.Present were Education ministry director general Leah Rotich, Knec acting CEO Mercy Karogo, and Centre for Mathematics, Science and Technology Education in Africa director Stephen Njoroge.A total of 942,021 candidates sat the KCPE exam last year, with only 5,143 candidates scoring 400 marks and above compared to 7,560 who posted similar grades the previous year, a 31 per cent drop.For KCSE, only 141 candidates scored an A plain out of about 570,000 candidates who sat the exam.Education CS Fred Matiang&rsquo;i said the performance was a true reflection of candidates&rsquo; results, without manipulation.He said all 88,929 students who scored between A and C+ will be absorbed into the universities.Some 4,645 candidates scored A-, while another 10,975 scored B+ with over 183,200 missing university slots.